  "texts": [
    "One key technique was to asynchronously launch requests to the judge LLM immediately after each response.",
    "This contrasts with the typical two-stage approach of gathering all responses first, then judging them.",
    "This technique is called \"LLM Judge Call Interweaving. \"",
    "With the typical twostage implementation, it would be necessary to wait for the slowest response to be completed before judging any response, which is a significant bottleneck.",
    "In contrast, launching judge tasks immediately for completed responses allows judge tasks to be completed while still generating responses.The pseudocode for this approach is shown below:LLMJudge Call Interweaving Pseudocode async function run_conversation_chain(model, persona): results = [] judge_tasks = [] messages = [persona] for each prompt in epistemic_prompts: messages.append(prompt) // Execute main LLM call result = await execute_call(model, messages) results.append(result) if result.response and not result.error: // Immediately spawn judge task (asynchronous) judge_task = async_spawn(judge_response(result)) judge_tasks.append(judge_task) // Continue building conversation history messages.append(result.response) else: break // Stop chain on error return results, judge_tasks async function main_experiment(): all_results = [] all_judge_tasks = [] // Execute all conversation chains concurrently for each (model, persona) combination: results, judge_tasks = await run_conversation_chain(model, persona) all_results.extend(results) all_judge_tasks.extend(judge_tasks) // Gather all judge results at the end judge_results = await gather_all(all_judge_tasks) return all_results, judge_results A.1 Performance MetricsThe implementation processed 30,120,383 tokens in 8.9 minutes (535.2 seconds) in a subset of the total 66,488,451 tokens, achieving a throughput of 56,068 tokens/sec when executed on a consumer laptop with a Snapdragon X Elite CPU."
  ],
